            <div>  <img loading="lazy" src="/sites/default/files/styles/partner_logo/public/2020-06/Evolution_Education_Outreach_logo.jpg?itok=KKQEVhja" width="245" height="56" alt="" typeof="foaf:Image" />


</div>
      </div>

<h2><span>Teaching evolution in U.S. public schools: a continuing challenge</span>
</h2>
<a href="https://evolution-outreach.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12052-020-00126-8">
<div class="field-field_type_of_study field-label-hidden">
            <div>Read the journal article</div>
      </div>
</a>
<div class="cover"><a href="https://evolution-outreach.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12052-020-00126-8"></a></div>
</div>
<div class="research-right">
    
<div class="field-field_topics field-label-hidden">
      <div>
              <div> Evolution education</div>
          </div>
  </div>

<div class="field-field_year field-label-hidden">
            <div>2020</div>
      </div>


<div class="field-field_body">

          <article><p><em><strong>Teaching evolution in U.S. public schools: a continuing challenge </strong></em>details a rigorous, nationwide NCSE/Penn State survey of high school biology teachers that finds promising and significant improvements in evolution education over the past 12 years — the last time a <a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.0060124">similar study</a> was conducted.</p></article>
    
</div>


